2. Query Processing Layer (Compute Layer)
This is where the Virtual Warehouses come in.
A Virtual Warehouse = a cluster of compute resources (CPU, memory, SSD cache) that runs queries.
You can spin up multiple warehouses for different workloads (ETL, BI dashboards, ML, etc.).
They are independent â†’ One teamâ€™s workload wonâ€™t affect anotherâ€™s.
Virtual warehouses can auto-scale up/down and pause/resume to save cost.
ğŸ“Œ Your notes point:
â€œQuery processing is done by Virtual Warehouses, which are independent compute clusters that can scale elastically and run concurrently.â€

3. Cloud Services Layer
This is the brain of Snowflake. It manages metadata, optimization, security, and overall orchestration.
Components:
Authentication & Access Control â†’ SSO, OAuth, MFA, Role-based security.
Infrastructure Manager â†’ Manages provisioning, scaling, failover, and resource allocation.
Optimizer â†’ Uses cost-based optimization for query execution (chooses best path).
Metadata Manager â†’ Tracks all metadata (tables, schemas, micro-partitions, stats, etc.) to make queries fast.
Security â†’ Data encryption, data masking, governance, role hierarchy.
